2660/A0/06/884/001.indicator_name: Proportion of children covered by government cash transfer programmes (number of children and % of total)
2660/A0/06/884/001.headline: UNICEF continues to engage with the Government and other stakeholders (the World Bank  CSOs) in the reform of the country's social transfer system  with a particular focus on improving their design by integrating various programs and making them child-sensitive.

2660/A0/06/884/002.indicator_name: Existence of monitoring and evaluation mechanisms to follow up on social protection delivery/system
2660/A0/06/884/002.headline: In collaboration with relevant partners  UNICEF is assessing  evaluating and improving capacity building activities for social protection staff with the aim of improving services for vulnerable children.

2660/A0/06/881/004.indicator_name: # of infants (under 2)  mother and baby centre nutrition services
2660/A0/06/881/004.headline: As the country is part of the route for refugees and migrants heading to EU countries  UNICEF is supporting local authorities in humanitarian response  by procurement of age-appropriate food  provision of nutrition counseling and appropriate referral to health services.

2660/A0/06/881/004.status_value: By March 2016  when refugees and migrants were transiting in the country  UNICEF reached more than 65 700 children in child-friendly spaces in Gevgelija and Tabanovce  670 were children with disabilities (29 Feb 2016 figures). Following the border closure in March  2016  the numbers are stable  with 1584 infants (under 2) accessing mother and baby care centre nutrition services and 124 mothers had access to relevant information and services on nutrition programme activities.
2660/A0/06/881/004.indicator_name: # of women benefited from infant and young child feeding counselling and awareness sessions at family support hubs  child friendly spaces and mother-baby corners
2660/A0/06/881/004.headline: As the country is part of the route for refugees and migrants heading to EU countries  UNICEF is supporting local authorities in humanitarian response  by procurement of age-appropriate food  provision of nutrition counseling and appropriate referral to health services.

2660/A0/05/502/001.status_value: The child justice data collection system was revised and is now fully operational. Indicators were reduced from 21 to 17 in order to simplify the data collection process and gender disaggregated data was introduced. The Council performed evaluation on the data collection process and noted significant improvement. Namely more than 90% of the institutions  the Public Prosecutors Office  police station  the basic courts with wider jurisdiction and the CSW  provided data. For the first time  the 201
2660/A0/05/502/001.indicator_name: State institutions use social inclusion and child-focused data  disaggregated by sex  in planning and budgeting social inclusion programmes
2660/A0/05/502/001.baseline_value: No regular use of child-focused data

2660/A0/05/502/001.status_value: the IR related to this indicator was discontinued in 2013
2660/A0/05/502/001.indicator_name: % of municipalities using child-related data for planning and budgeting for children

2660/A0/05/502/003.status_value: National Child Rights Commission produces annual reports on the situation of children  with gradual move towards use of relevant indicators and data for reporting.
2660/A0/05/502/003.indicator_name: National Commission on children rights regularly and timely produces a report on the situation of children using a set of internationally accepted child-well-being indicators

2660/A0/05/502/003.status_value: Two reports on child rights prepared by NGO coalitions and published in 2012.
2660/A0/05/502/003.indicator_name: # of thematic reports on children rights prepared by the NGO coalition and presented to the National Child Rights Commission and other relevant institutions

2660/A0/05/502/002.status_value: In 2013  1.2 per cent of the national budget was spent on social protection for children. This includes only Child Allowance  Parental Allowance  Special Child Allowance and One-Time Financial Assistance for Newborns. The overall increase is due to the significant increase in payments for Parental Allowance (a non-poverty oriented cash benefit aimed at raising birth rates). The increase in parental allowance spending compensates for a huge decrease (34% since 2010) in the number of beneficiaries
2660/A0/05/502/002.indicator_name: % of national budget spent on social protection for children (exclusively on: Social financial assistance  child benefits and special child allowance)

2660/A0/05/502/002.status_value: In 2013  an estimated 10.9 per cent of children were covered by social protection programmes. This includes Child Allowance  Special Child Allowance  One-time Financial Assistance for Newborns  and Parental Allowance.
2660/A0/05/502/002.indicator_name: % of children covered by social protection programmes (includes SFA  child benefits and SCA)

2660/A0/05/502/002.status_value: IR was officially revised in 2012. No updated estimation is yet available
2660/A0/05/502/002.indicator_name: % of children with special needs attending school

Furthermore  the alliance builds on C4D activities and aims to increase awareness of the importance of ECD and the role of parents in stimulating early childhood development.  Implementation of the alliance will be carried out in 2

2660/A0/05/502/004.baseline_value: No company with child rights advocacy as part of its CSR in the country

2660/A0/05/502/004.status_value: The CO strategy for improving quality CRC related reporting and addressing gaps was to conduct regular informal media briefings on child rights issues- as a result of five briefings 15 media outlets produced quality media reports.
2660/A0/05/502/004.indicator_name: # of media outlets that apply revised standards on media reporting
2660/A0/05/502/004.baseline_value: Media reporting standards have gaps in protecting the best interest of children

2660/A0/05/502/004.status_value: The Parliament Working Group for Children  established in 2011  has actively organized advocacy initiatives (five field visits  one public hearing  one thematic discussion during commission meeting) to support changes in juvenile justice law  family law as related to adoption procedures and draft ECD law.
2660/A0/05/502/004.indicator_name: The Parliamentary Child Rights body regularly advises law makers on the impact of new legislation on children's rights
2660/A0/05/502/004.baseline_value: No parliamentary child rights body exists

2660/A0/06/883/004.indicator_name: UNICEF-targeted children in humanitarian situations benefitting from psychosocial support
2660/A0/06/883/004.headline: Child protection services  including psychosocial support  information and awareness raising activities  identification and referral of vulnerable cases were provided to 170 refugees and migrant children and their families  and 38 unaccompanied and separated children  as part of UNICEF's emergency response.

2660/A0/06/883/002.indicator_name: "Municipalities that implement local protocols for the protection of children from violence  abuse and neglect "
2660/A0/06/883/002.headline: Action was taken to improve outcomes for children abused  neglected  or exposed to violence.  A training package and pool of experts were made available to support the capacity building of multi-agency teams in development of child centered individual care plans that will make a difference for these vulnerable children.

2660/A0/06/883/003.indicator_name: Decrease in the percentage of parents who find it justified to use a violent disciplining method in at least one given circumstance
2660/A0/06/883/003.headline: UNICEF's work in positive parenting will contribute to addressing the persistent use of violent discipline  by introducing and promoting a positive discipline approach for parents  legal guardians and professionals as a proven method that contributes to prevention of abuse  neglect and violence against children.

2660/A0/05/501/001.status_value: Some progress to report from the baseline. Two national strategies (Safe Motherhood and Immunization) remain well resourced. Roma Decade Action Plan on Health has significant increase in resource allocation in 2013 and 2014. Health Action Plan on Disability is under revision. New cross-sectoral strategy on children with disability is in process of development.
2660/A0/05/501/001.indicator_name: # of fully resourced national MCH strategies targeting MCH disparities (Safe Motherhood Strategy  Immunization  Health Action Plan on Disability  Roma Decade Action Plan on Health)

2660/A0/05/501/001.status_value: Consultation process with the Government to formally assess % of implementation of national MCH strategies will be carried out in the course of 2015.

Evidence-based guidelines for early detection/care for children with developmental difficulties and nutrition related developmental risks included in mandatory in-service training for patronage nurses

2660/A0/05/501/001.status_value: 22 million USD allocated for rehabilitation of community MCH services for the following three years (15 million USD pledged from the Government  as part of the current investment plan  and 8 million USD grant from the Dutch Government)  as a result of UNICEF technical assistance  advocacy and leveraging. This should provide over 80% funds for the implementation of the key MCH strategies  i.e. Immunization  Safe Motherhood  and Nutrition.
2660/A0/05/501/001.indicator_name: % of sufficiently resourced annual national MCH programmes targeting MCH disparities

2660/A0/05/501/001.status_value: Given that fiscal decentralization in the health sector has not yet taken place  instead of supporting local health planning as was initially foreseen  the programme provided technical assistance to the national health authorities to start modernising public health programing  account for local disparities and introduce evidence-based planning. Initial agreements were made in the MTR consultation meetings to change this indicator as part of the formal MTR process to take place in the first half
2660/A0/05/501/001.indicator_name: % of municipalities with MCH indicators below national average that have increased financial resources for MCH programmes

2660/A0/06/885/001.indicator_name: Number of studies and/or research on issues of relevance to the rights of most marginalized children conducted by the Ombudsman Office
